$G$, finite group  
$K$, field

A $K$-representation of $G$ is a homomorphism $\chi: G \to \text{GL}(n,K)$.

$n$ is called the **degree** of $\chi$.

$K$-reprs $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{Y}$ of $G$, both of degree $n$,
are **similar** if there exists an invertible $n\times n$ matrix $P$
over $K$ s.t. $\mathcal{Y}(g) = p^{-1}\mathcal{X}(g)P$, $∀g\in G$

$K[G]$, group algebra

If $\mathcal{X}$ is $K$-repr of $G$ with degree $n$,
then $\mathcal{X}$ can be extended linearly to $K[G]$.
The result is an algebra homomorphism $\mathcal{X}:K[G]\to M_n(K)$, where
$M_n(K)$ is the algebra of $n\times n$ matrices.

Assuming that $K$ is algebraically closed, the $K$-repr $\mathcal{X}$ of $G$
is irreducible iff $\mathcal{X}$ maps $K[G]$ to a full algebra $M_n(K)$.

$K=\mathbb{C}$  
$\mathbf{Z}$, centre

$$
\mathbb{C}[G]=\sum_{i=1}^{k} M_{n_i}(\mathbb{C})
$$

$k=\text{dim}(\mathbf{Z}(\mathbb{C}[G]))$ = number of classes of $G$.

$$
|G| = \text{dim}(\mathbb{C}[G]) = \sum_{i=1}^k (n_i)^2
$$

$G\to \mathbb{C}[G] \to$  
(projection to the $i$th summand)  
$M_{n_i}(\mathbb{C})$ is an irreducible $\mathbb{C}$-repr of $G$

write $\mathcal{X}_i$ to denote this repr

Every irred $\mathcal{C}$-repr of $G$ is similar to one of the $\mathcal{X}_i$

Given a $\mathbb{C}$-repr $\chi$ of $G$, the associated **character** $\chi$
is the function $G\to \mathbb{C}$ given by $\chi(g)=\text{trace}(\mathcal{X}(g))$.

We say $\mathcal{X}$ affords $\chi$.
Similar repr afford equal characters.

If $\mathcal{X}$ affords $\chi$ then $\chi(1)$ is the degree of
$\mathcal{X}$, it is called the **degree of** $\chi$.

$\chi(x^{-1}gx) = \chi(g)$, so characters are constant on conjugacy
classes.

If $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are characters of $G$ afforded by $U$ and $V$ respectively,
then the representation $\mathcal{X}$ given by 
$$
\mathcal{X}(g) =
\begin{pmatrix}
U(g) & 0 \\
0    & V(g)
\end{pmatrix}
$$

affords the character $\chi = \alpha + \beta$

Sums of characters are characters. A character that is not a sum of two
characters is said to be **irreducible**.
Every character is a sum of irreducible characters.

Every character is a sum of irreducible characters.

