$\chi_0$ principal character = 1.

The **principal** character $1_G$ of $G$ is the trivial homomorphism,
with constant value $1$.

A character $\chi(\text{mod} q)$ is induced by $\chi_1(\text{mod} q_1)$, $q_1|q$
if $\chi(n)=\chi_1(n)$ for $(n,q)=1$.

A character $\chi$ is uniquely a sum of irred character.
These are called the irreducible constituents of $\chi$.

A character $\chi(\text{mod} q)$ is called **primitive** if it
is not induced by a character of a smaller modulus.

A **linear** character is a character $\gamma$ s.t. the degree $\gamma(1)=1$

The number of linear characters of $G$ is $|G : G'|$

$\text{Irr}(G)$ ist the set of irred characters of $G$.

Theorem:
The characters afforded by the $\chi_i$ are distinct and linearly idependent,
and they form the set $\mathrm{Irr}(G)$

$$
\sum_{\chi\in\text{Irr}(G)} {\underbrace{\chi(1)}_{\text{degree}}}^2 = |G|
$$

$|\text{Irr}(G)|=k$, the number of conjugacy classes of $G$.

$G$ is abelian iff every member of $\text{Irr}(G)$ has degree $1$. $G$
is abelian iff $k=|G|$.

The set $\text{Irr}(G)$ is a basis for the space $\text{cf}(G)$ of
class functions.

Let $\mathcal{X}$ be a repr of $G$ with degree $d$ and let $g\in G$
have order $n$. Then $\mathcal{X}(g)^n=I$, the $d\times d$ identical
matrix.

The matrix $\mathcal{X}(g)$ is simila to a diagonal matrix whose diagonal entries are nth
roots of unity.

If $\mathcal{X}$ affords the char $\chi$, then $\chi(g) =
\text{trace}(\mathcal{X}(g)) = \epsilon_1 + \dots + \epsilon_d$, where
$\epsilon_i$ for $1\leq i \leq d$ are nth root of unity.

$\chi(g^{-1}) = \text{trace}(\mathcal{X}(g)^{-1} = \bar\epsilon_1 \dots
\bar\epsilon_d = \overline{\chi(g)}$

theorem:

Let $\chi$ be a char of a group $G$, where $\chi$ is afforded by a repr $\mathcal{X}$, and let $g \in G$. Then

(a) $|\chi(g)| \le \chi(1)$  
(b) $|\chi(g)| = \chi(1)$ iff $\mathcal{X}(g)$ is a scalar matrix  
(c) $\chi(g) = \chi(1)$ iff $\mathcal{X}(g)$ is the identity matrix
